=== Format strings ===

This is probably the most powerful aspect of <tt>eix</tt>, but the documentation is hard to understand. <tt>eix</tt> has a mini-language for specifying more precise queries and output formats than are possible using only the basic options. The format string is specified as the option argument to the <code>--format</code> option. There are basically two major concepts: properties and variables.

* '''Properties:''' Each package has a set of associated properties that can either be printed or used as part of a predicate in a conditional block.
* '''Variables:''' A variable can be any environment variable set in the environment of eix, or any of the variables printed from the output of <tt>eix --dump</tt>.

==== Conditional blocks ====

Conditional blocks take can 3 forms, each with an optional RHS, each of which can be optionally negated:

{{CodeBox|title=If-then string comparison|<pre>{[!]PROPERTY=RHS}TCODE{}</pre>}}
{{CodeBox|title=If-then predicate|<pre>{[!]PROPERTY}TCODE{}</pre>}}
{{CodeBox|title=If-then-else string comparison|<pre>{[!]PROPERTY=RHS}TCODE{else}FCODE{}</pre>}}
{{CodeBox|title=If-then-else predicate|<pre>{[!]PROPERTY}TCODE{else}FCODE{}</pre>}}
{{CodeBox|title=Assignment|<pre>{[!]*VARIABLE=RHS}</pre>}}
{{CodeBox|title=Assign 1 or empty string|<pre>{[!]*VARIABLE}</pre>}}

== Tips ==
=== Tmux users should disable status line updates ===
If you use tmux with automatic window renaming, that is you have <code>set -g automatic-rename on</code> in your tmux config, you probably want to disable status line updates. Otherwise, every time you run eix-update, the title of your window will be renamed to something like <tt>eix-update: Finished*</tt>.

To disable status line updates, run the following command:

{{RootCmd|<nowiki>echo "NOSTATUSLINE=true" >> /etc/eixrc/00-eixrc</nowiki>}}

